<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>NAHT is an independent trade union and professional association with 28,500 members in England, Wales and Northern Ireland</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0091</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">NAHT </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NAHT is an independent trade union and professional association with 28,500 members in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Members include head teachers, deputies, assistant head teachers, bursars and school business managers.  They hold leadership positions in early years, primary, special, secondary and independent schools, sixth form colleges, outdoor education centres, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pupil referral units, social service establishments and other education settings.  The membership represents 40 per cent of secondary and 85 per cent of primary schools in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and this places us in an excellent position to r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">espond to this call for evidence.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 41.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">NAHT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">does not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">oppose </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the voluntary conversion of academies and has always recognised the potential for innovation offered by diversity of provision. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Many of our members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> lead academies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We believe that school leaders are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">often best placed to make strategic decisions about what is best for their individual school community and, for some, academy status provides freedom from political interference in operational decisions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 41.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">e do not seek to defend long term under-performance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and recognise that difficult decisions may need to be made after other forms of support have been offered. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">However, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">serious </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">concerns about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">implementation of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">government’s policy of forced academisation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of academisation i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">n narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 41.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Good practice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘closing the gap’ between groups of pupils is not and has never been the sole domain of academies and one need only look at the success of projects like London Challenge to see that it is the work that goes on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> schools rather than their governance st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ructure that makes the difference. There are numerous local authority schools that are equally successful at closing the gap. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 41.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some schools have improved rapidly since becoming academies and many have been successful in closing the attainment gap between d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ifferent groups of pupils. However, there is also evidence to suggest that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of those schools had, at the time of academisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> already established working practices destined to deliver significant improvement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">one school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">West Midlan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> delivered impressive results</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> moving from 38% Level 4 in English in Maths in 2008</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to 60% in 2011 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at which point </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they were compelled to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">convert</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is not an isolated example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: schools selected for sponsored academy status are not always the lowest perf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">orming schools in their area.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 41.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> diminish the remarkable achievements of many academies, certainly those within the secondary sector, that have increased the life chances of the young people and communities they serve. We would simply reinforce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the point that it is the quality of teaching and leadership and the support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that is in place for a school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in terms of parental support, capital and human resources, etc. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that are the greater determinant of success than school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">type</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We would warn strongly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> against seeing structural reforms as a panacea for school i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mprovement, despite their seemin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g simplicity to track and manage from the centre; structural change is at best a means to an end and at worst a distraction. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 41.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NAHT has previously expressed the view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the academy and free school programme may not translate to a primary setting as easily as government suggested.  Some primaries are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">able</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to manage the increased administration; others </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cannot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Primaries have always depended more than secondaries on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">external support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and sponsors have been noticeably reluctant to work with small and/or rural primaries. The focus on academisation as the main strategy for school improvement, at a time of significant cut backs in local authority support, has left many pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">imaries feeling stranded as they face in 2014 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a huge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> programme of change. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 41.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This view has been reinforced not only by the relatively low take up of academy status amongst primary schools (fewer than 10%), but also by the recent school performance data which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> shows that free schools and sponsored primary academies were the two worst performing groups of schools both in terms of attainment at level 4 or above in reading, writing, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rammar, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pelling and punctuation and in terms of the percentage of pupils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">making </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expected progress.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Percentage of pupils achieving level 4 or above and level 5 or above in key stage 2 tests and teacher assessments by school type</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; float:right; margin:0pt 9pt; width:389.3pt"><tr style="height:35.1pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:91.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:bottom; width:21.05pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td colspan="3" style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; borde