amily:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similarly, the recent Annual Report from Ofsted highlighted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt">At 57%, the proportion of good and outstanding sponsor-led academies is still lower than the figure </span><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt">for all schools nationally.</span><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt">NAHT is </span><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt">mindful that over 30 academy trusts have recently received pre-warning letters. </span><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt">Once again, this does not mean that academies cannot and do not succeed, but that such success is not guaranteed.</span><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The process for establi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">shing,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">academies and free schools, including working with sponsors</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NAHT believes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsible innovation should be encouraged, particularly where students are not currently well served by the existing mainstream system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; as may be the case in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some areas for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">special needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and alternative provision, for example.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, we also believe that we should develop our schools without damaging those around us.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, whilst we remain supportive of the principle of establish</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of innovative schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and academies in areas of need, we are clear that free schools and academies should not be set up where their presence will damage the viability of existing good schools and that all schools should operate a fair admissions policy to ensure a level playin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g field. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We state this as we remain concerned about the tactics </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">used</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to increase the number of academies and free schools in the system. These tactics </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sometimes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">appear to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">focused on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quantity rather than quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Importantly, in the eyes of the professi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on, short-comings in the systems and processes surrounding the establishment of these schools tarnish the reputation of the academies programme and make it harder for committed school leaders to deliver improvements to the education system as a whole. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">particular, NAHT would highlight as areas of concern:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The use of financial incentives to encourage conversion to academy status </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Undue pressure / intimidation of school leaders and governing bodies to convert </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lack of process / transparency in the select p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rocess and criteria for the selection of sponsors</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lack of coordination and planning – especially in relation to free schools and primary schools places</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Poor treatment of school leaders during / immediately following conversion</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Inaccurate information provided by the Department for Education, particularly in relation to sponsors and the school in their chains. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Financial incentives to encourage conversion to academy status</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At a time of budget cuts and increasing austerity for schools, NAHT is troubled by the amount of resource being devoted to the marketing and promotion of the academies programme to schools that are not in need of support. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department for Education has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dramatically reduced the amount of guidance and support materials available for schools and yet is producing marketing materials like ‘Primary Academy Magazine’ and is offering a time-limited additional funding package of £50k for each group of three schoo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ls converting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to academy status</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We question whether this represents best use of resources for schools or good value for money for the tax-payer.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One of the reasons for our concern about how academisation is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">communicated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to primary schools is our awareness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the difficulties encountered by our members who have converted and now have academy status. Large secondary schools are better prepared to assume the administrative burdens of academy status and are already able to benefit from larger scale commissioni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng for products and services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> etc. Many of our members have highlighted how difficult they have found it undertaking all of the work previously undertaken by the local authority on their behalf, and also how expensive even a small group of primary schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can find services they now need to commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> them for themselves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be encouraging schools to take their time in considering the potential implications of an irreversible change in school structure, rather than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">incentivizing swift action with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">offer of short term funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Undue pressure / intimidation of school leaders and governing bodies to convert</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The decision to convert to academy status should not be made on the basis of intimidation and/or misinformation and yet we continue to receive re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ports of large numbers of members being placed under undue pressure to convert to academy status. Some of our members have reported threats that they will lose their jobs if they don’t convert, others have been told that governors and school leaders can ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve no say in the selection of sponsors.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Schools are dependent on the goodwill and support of their parent body for much of their success, not to mention the goodwill of the teachers and pupils. Forcing academisation upon a school and community that oppos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es it can be counter-productive as a long and drawn-out process can become a distraction from the important business of school improvement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is a view shared by Ofsted Inspectors as illustrated by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Section 8 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inspection report of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Woodhouse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Primary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">School</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (now</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> closed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) from January 2013, which states:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The process of converting to an academy has placed a high demand on the energies of governors, the head</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">teacher and other senior leaders and it has distracted them from focusing on improving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the quality of teaching and learning.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The same point is made more powerfully still in the report on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ley</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">land</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Methodist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Junior</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">School</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in March 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Another significant barrier to improvement has been the amount of time the headteacher has been involved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the discussions about transferring to an academy. Given the headteacher has been without a deputy headteacher or any senior leader for most of the autumn term her time has been too stretched. Lengthy and time-consuming meetings with parents, unions, sta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ff and external agencies have taken leaders’ and governors’ focus away from school improvement and building capacit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y to improve within the school.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many schools know what they need to do improve, but may need time for strategies to bear fruit. For other schools, there may need to be some changes of personnel at all levels, but structural reform is not required for this to occur. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of process / tra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nsparency in the selection process and criteria for the selection of sponsors</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our members who have been through the ‘forced academisation’ process have reported that there has been little or no discussion about why a particular sponsor or choice of two spo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been chosen for them. Indeed many school leaders contact us in search of information about sponsors and what they might be able to offer in terms of school improvement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are happy to point schools in the direction of sponsors that suit their ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eds and actively facilitate such contact. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is particularly the case with sponsors who have a strong reputation within the secondary sector, but little or no track record at primary. Often the impression is given that a sponsor has suggested that they w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ant schools in a given area and the Department is working harder to meet the needs of the sponsor than it is to meet the specific needs of a school in challenging circumstances.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">North London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local authority,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for example,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> one school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decided</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to seek a sponsor voluntarily but were denied their choice (an existing accredited chain). After a long period of conflict, the Department’s replacement sponsor pulled out and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> allowed to proceed with their original choice; this wasted a gre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at deal of time. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of coordination and planning – especially in relation to free schools and primary schools places</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NAHT is very aware of the shortage of primary places in the system and the fact that this situation is likely to increase in coming y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ears. In this context, it is remarkable that the £1.1 billion pounds invested in the free schools programme has not been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fully</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">targeted at either the sector or the geographical regions most in need of new places.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As we commented to the committee’s inquiry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">into school places, local challenges are exacerbated by the fact that Local Authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cannot easily</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> affect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the planned admission numbers in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> academies in their area, resulting in some local authority schools having to absorb a disproportionate number of n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ew places; places which they will physically struggle to accommodate without resorting to temporary classrooms or a loss of other facilities.       </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Poor treatment of school leaders during / immediately following conversion</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our members undergoing conversio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n to sponsored academy status continue to be told that TUPE does not apply to school leaders and that it is legitimate for them to lose their post as part of the conversion process. Often it is suggested that they should ‘take a deal’ and leave to allow th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e new sponsor a ‘free hand’. This can occur irrespective of the performance of the head teacher prior to conversion. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Increasingly we are also receiving reports of school leaders who are allowed to TUPE over to a new academy, but immediately subject to so </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">called ‘benchmarking’ assessments of their role which then result in their demotion within the academy structure. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Inaccurate information provided by the Department for Education, particularly in relation to sponsors and the school in their chains. </span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Like many interested parties, NAHT monitors the monthly reports provided by the Department for Education on new academies and free schools and those in the pipeline. Like many others, we are becoming increasingly frustrated that the data often does not acc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urately reflect the number of schools converting as part of a named chain and by the number of general errors and omissions in the data.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recent high profile events hav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e illustrated the shortcomings of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">centralised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">system that has looked to structural reform as its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">main</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strategy for improving school performance. The question of ‘what will happen when an academy fails?’ has been asked right from the start of this process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Sadly the only answers that have been offered to date are to close the school or to seek a new trust to take its place. Neither of these approaches gets to the heart of the matter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">address the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">reasons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for under-performance and the challenges faced by s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ome of our school communities. This again reinforces our assertion that academy status </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may be appropriate but, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in and of itself</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> does not make the fundamental difference to school performance. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school collaboration and support is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> effective and efficient way of delivering improvement across the system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which is why NAHT is currently piloting two school improvement projects ‘Aspire’ and ‘Instead’ based on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er assessment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Alternatives to sponsored </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">academy status for failing primary schools</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It has been demonstrated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">repeatedly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the best way to achieve sustained improvement in the school system is to build strong school communities based on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vision, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">collaboration and trust. School leaders, teachers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and pupils alike can all learn a tremendous amount from their peers and, as p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rogrammes like London Challenge and City Challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have demonstrated, success can be contagious. Because peer support mechanisms rely upon educators rather than policy makers and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> politicians, they more easily gain the trust of the school workforce, paving the way for open and constructive dialogue. These peer networks are far from easy, but they work. Many of our inner cities have benefitted from such an approach and we believe ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ny more schools around the country could benefit in equal measure. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The experience of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> those jurisdictions identified as high performing by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">PISA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would also seem to bear out this belief.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is why NAHT has been consistent in its view that increased competit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ion between schools and the use of market forces may create pockets of excellence but will not deliver system wide improvements on a national scale. Market forces are a weak mechanism for reducing inequality in education outcomes as the ability to choose i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s itself unevenly distributed. The recent Sutton Trust report makes this point clearly. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 45pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Primary schools are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">small organisations coping with heavy workloads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This is why we believe that a system for school improvement that builds upon, rather than undermines </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">collective purpose is required. Where academy solutions have been successful for primary schools, it has been where they have built on existing col</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">laborations and partnerships. This is why we believe that other methods for supporting primary schools, such as the establishment of trusts, federations and other formal support arrangements with an accredited partner should be permissible. We believe that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the creation of strong federal relationships between schools will then increase the desire for autonomy as their capacity to cope with it grow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> DfE 2013 National curriculum assessments at key stage 2:2012 to 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Ofsted 2013 The Report of Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector of Education, Children’s Services and Skills </span></p></body></html>